5.24.23  10:26 pm   building on the question someone else asked, how can you really differentiate, say, A# minor from Bb minor?

     they sound the same, but on paper they look different. on paper, the key of Bb minor will have a lot of flats in the key signature. the key of A# minor will have a lot of sharps in the key signature. and in A# minor, all the note heads will be written slightly lower on the page

     even if we take their relative majors, they're still the same thing. also what did you mean by change by more than 6 degrees?

     adding or taking a way more than 6 sharps or flats. more than 6 moves around the circle of fifths

     could you give me an example of that?

     going from the key of Ab to E, on paper is like adding 8 sharps, but really it's gonna sound more like adding 4 flats

      could you also give me an example of, say, a progression where there's a clear difference between A# minor and Bb minor?

     on paper, everything is different. by sound, nothing is different. no need for examples. it's everything or nothing, depending on whether you are talking about the way it sounds or the way it looks
